Similarly the  branes become wrapped  branes. 
On the -branes the gauge theory is a  five dimensional gauge 
theory 
compactified on a circle of radius . 
This is the generalization to quiver  theories of the deconstructed 
models. 

In the following we will consider the deconstructed quiver theories
both at small and large coupling constant. In particular we
will focus on the Wilson lines.
At weak coupling the Wilson lines can be understood by moving one
of the branes of a stack to infinity and identifying the open
string state connecting the stack of   branes to the brane
at infinity as a static quark. Such an open string can wind 
times around the orbifold. This is easily pictured on the orbifold
covering space where the string connects  branes belonging to
different sectors. We will refer to this situation as twisted  
quarks. 



At strong coupling we will
obtain relevant information from the supergravity solution generated by 
the 
stacks of D3 branes. It has to be noticed that the supergravity 
background with 
branes  
displaced to  various points of the circle of radius  has a constant
dilaton. Hence the gauge theory coupling constant does not run with
the energy scale (which is related by the UV/IR principle to the
radial distance scale in the bulk geometry). When we pass to the
orbifold the same is obviously true. 

However one has to keep in mind
that there is a tachyonic twisted mode  at the centre of the 
orbifold which leads to an instability.  The behaviour of 
the 
dilaton
may become non-trivial  leading to the fact that a running
coupling  may  be generated at this stage.  For the part of the geometry 
relevant for the calculation of the static
potential between static quarks along the deconstructed fifth dimension,
and for , the static potential should  not be 
affected by 
this tachyonic instability if the 
change of geometry is confined to a finite region,  close to the centre 
of the 
orbifold. A more detailed study of this 
instability is out of the scope of the present paper, but certainly 
deserves 
further 
investigation.



Rectangular  Wilson Loop at Small Coupling 

The appearance of a perturbative extra-dimension 
in the large  regime can be investigated by computing the 
quark-quark potential
in the static approximation. It is expected that a  
dependence of the 
potential in the inter-quark 
distance  should appear as required by  a five-dimensional 
interpretation. 
We will show that this is indeed the case. Moreover we will be interested 
in 
the 
potential between quarks
belonging to different twisted sectors of the orbifold. Indeed in the 
universal 
cover 
of the orbifold one can place quarks in different sectors identified 
under the 
orbifold action. 
We will compute the potential as a function of the angle 
between the quarks in the universal cover. In particular we focus on an 
orbifold 
action on only one plane, i.e.
 
corresponding to
 
In the following we will focus on the simplest situation 
,
sketched  in Fig.1. 


