We expect in the deconstructed 
case to find
at weak coupling
a leading  behaviour in the untwisted sector (two quarks in the 
same 
sector) while
there should be a non-trivial angular dependence in the twisted case


Now the behaviour of these integrals depend on the relative size
of the terms  and .  in any case the second 
term will 
dominate at large distances. 
Let us denote by  the distance where the angular momentum term
starts dominating due to its slower decay at infinity.
For sake of simplification, in the following we will focus on the case 
where 
,
i.e. when the angular momentum term dominates everywhere outside the
deconstruction region. In this case, one can use the deconstruction 
metrics  
() below  and neglect   everywhere 
outside. This 
is achieved when the contribution to
 from the deconstruction region is large enough. 

In the opposite case,  there exists an intermediate region 
, 
where one has to use the more complicated  interpolating metrics defined 
by 
(). We postpone this case to  further work. 




